Defendant Dre Kwon Lavelle Swopes in court with attorney Darryl Everett Smith.  Defendant Dre Kwon Lavelle Swopes in custody.  William R. F. Ackell and later in the hearing, Stephan Nolten appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: SD.
Court finds State has complied with victim notification.  Sentencing hearing proceeded. Statements made as to sentencing.

AS TO COUNT 2: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 42 MONTHS, with credit for 90 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 24 MONTHS.

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and IS eligible for the "Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program". 
Upon successful completion of the Substance Abuse Program, Court will allow release of initial confinement within 30 days of notice to Court.  Remaining time will convert to extended supervision.

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION AND EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
-No new laws rising to the level of probable cause;
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent;
-No driving without a valid drivers license.
-Not to operate, ride in, or be present in any stolen cars;
-Obtain/maintain employment/school;
-Obtain an HSED/GED/High school diploma;
-Letter of apology to the victim;
-Perform 25 hours of community service;
-Court sets restitution at $0.
-No contact with firearms;
-Provide DNA sample;
-Pay all mandatory supervision fees, court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA surcharges during period of probation.  If revoked, all applicable surcharges and assessments are to be collected by DOC at a rate which the department deems reasonable from the defendant's funds and during extended supervision; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
-Court waives all non-mandatory fees and costs.

*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
